article.description:
Jess Brungo scored 23 points and Kelly
Mazzante added 16 as 12th-ranked Penn State defeated No. 9 Purdue
80-68 Thursday night.
article.headline: Penn State's lead over Purdue now 2½ games
article.linkText: Brungo fuels Penn State's upset of No. 9 Purdue
article.story:
STATE COLLEGE, Pa. (AP) -- Penn State is not a one-woman team
anymore, and that's bad news for the rest of the Big Ten.

	   Jess Brungo scored 23 points and Kelly Mazzante had 16 -- nine
below her average -- as No. 12 Penn State defeated No. 9 Purdue
80-68 on Thursday night.

	   "Every time Kelly's on the floor, people are focusing on her,''
Brungo said. "She's such a great scorer, and it really opens the
floor.''

	   Opponents have spent the last three years trying to stop
Mazzante, who led the nation in scoring last year as a sophomore.
Often when teams held Mazzante in check, they came away with a win.

	   But for the second straight game, the Lady Lions (21-5, 11-1)
overcame a subpar showing from their star. Last Sunday at Michigan
State, Mazzante had just eight points, but Jess Strom had 19 and
Tanisha Wright and Jennifer Brenden each scored 12 to lead Penn
State to a 64-60 win.

	   Against Purdue (19-4, 8-3), the Lady Lions didn't need a lot of
points from Mazzante. Wright had 15 points and Strom had 14 points
and 10 rebounds.

	   "The balance of this team really helped us,'' Penn State coach
Rene Portland said. "That's when we're successful, and that's when
this team is at its best, what it should be. We predicted coming
into this season that we'd have that balance, and it has developed
really positively.''

	   Penn State won despite a near-perfect game from Purdue's Shereka
Wright, who scored 24 points and hit her first 13 shots -- seven
field goals and six free throws. Wright finished 8-of-13 from the
floor and hit all eight of her free throws.

	   "She's a great player, and that's what great players do,'' said
Tanisha Wright, who guarded Shereka Wright for much of the first
half. "She had a great game. Just unfortunately for her, a lot of
players for us had great games.''

	   The win gave Penn State a 2½-game lead over Purdue in the league
standings. Either Purdue or Penn State has won the regular season
in each of the last four seasons and six of the last nine.

	   Brungo hit a 3-pointer to start the second half, and Strom made
a layup to put Penn State up 49-40 with 18:50 left.

	   "You would've thought I fed them Benadryl at halftime and we
were asleep or something,'' Purdue coach Kristy Curry said.

	   The Boilermakers pulled within three points three times in the
second half, the last when Mary Jo Noon hit two free throws to make
it 59-56 with 11:24 left.

	   But Strom hit a long 3-pointer and Tanisha Wright scored the
next two baskets to start an 11-2 run that put Penn State up 70-58
with 6:19 left.

	   Erika Valek scored 15 points for Purdue before fouling out with
1:05 left, and Noon scored 11. The Boilermakers hit 26 of 29 free
throws, more than double Penn State in both made and attempted.

	   With 7:49 left in the first half and the score tied at 29,
Brungo hit a 3-pointer to start a 7-0 run that put Penn State up
for good. The Lady Lions led 44-40 at halftime and never trailed in
the second.
